12
00:00:28,820 --> 00:00:31,000
Never thought I’d miss the A train.

13
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:32,640
Organizers in Hong Kong said more than

14
00:00:32,640 --> 00:00:35,580
one million people hit the streets on Sunday.

15
00:00:35,580 --> 00:00:39,460
They’re protesting Hong Kong’s controversial
extradition bill.

16
00:00:39,460 --> 00:00:41,090
If the bill gets passed,

17
00:00:41,090 --> 00:00:44,620
it would allow Chinese authorities to order
Hong Kong authorities

18
00:00:44,620 --> 00:00:48,850
to arrest and deport suspected criminals to
mainland China.

19
00:00:48,850 --> 00:00:52,730
This is a big deal because a lot of so-called
“crimes” in mainland China

20
00:00:52,730 --> 00:00:56,370
are not crimes in Hong Kong or other free
countries-slash-regions.

21
00:00:56,370 --> 00:00:59,970
Crimes like, wanting more democracy and rule
of law.

22
00:00:59,970 --> 00:01:02,399
Or being a Catholic bishop.

23
00:01:02,399 --> 00:01:05,100
The version of the bill on the Hong Kong Legislature’s
website

24
00:01:05,100 --> 00:01:07,890
says the extradition bill applies only to
crimes

25
00:01:07,890 --> 00:01:10,740
that are “punishable in Hong Kong with imprisonment

26
00:01:10,740 --> 00:01:12,750
for more than 3 years.”

27
00:01:12,750 --> 00:01:14,810
But because of pressure, at the end of May,

28
00:01:14,810 --> 00:01:17,110
Hong Kong’s Secretary for Security said
they would change

29
00:01:17,110 --> 00:01:21,510
the threshold to crimes punishable only by
7 or more years.

30
00:01:21,510 --> 00:01:22,510
And then everyone was like,

31
00:01:22,510 --> 00:01:24,159
ok that sounds reasonable,

32
00:01:24,159 --> 00:01:25,420
problem solved everyone,

33
00:01:25,420 --> 00:01:26,670
nothing to worry about.

34
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:28,040
Just kidding.

35
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:29,210
People are still unhappy,

36
00:01:29,210 --> 00:01:32,710
because that doesn’t change the fundamental
problem with the bill.

37
00:01:32,710 --> 00:01:37,130
The fundamental problem is that Hongkongers
don’t trust Beijing.

38
00:01:37,130 --> 00:01:38,159
And by extension,

39
00:01:38,159 --> 00:01:41,400
they no longer trust the Hong Kong government.

40
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:43,810
A lot of Hong Kongers believe the bill itself

41
00:01:43,810 --> 00:01:47,960
is simply the first step the Chinese Communist
Party’s larger plan

42
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:51,360
to water down Hong Kong’s freedoms and rule
of law—

43
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:54,860
so Hong Kong eventually operates like the
rest of China.

44
00:01:54,860 --> 00:01:56,390
With arbitrary arrest.

45
00:01:56,390 --> 00:01:57,650
And torture.

46
00:01:57,650 --> 00:01:59,360
Who could forget torture?

47
00:01:59,360 --> 00:02:01,670
Hong Kong’s really been missing out on the
torture

48
00:02:01,670 --> 00:02:04,240
that mainland Chinese dissidents enjoy everyday.

49
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:07,070
Of course, when the Chinese Communist Party

50
00:02:07,070 --> 00:02:11,319
forced the UK to turn over Hong Kong to China
in 1997,

51
00:02:11,319 --> 00:02:14,239
they signed the “Sino-British Joint Declaration.”

52
00:02:14,239 --> 00:02:16,859
It promised “50 years, no change”—meaning,

53
00:02:16,859 --> 00:02:21,879
they would not infringe on Hong Kong’s laws
for at least 50 years.

54
00:02:21,879 --> 00:02:25,279
But this extradition bill is a clear violation
of that promise.

55
00:02:25,279 --> 00:02:27,590
Not that we didn’t see it coming.

56
00:02:27,590 --> 00:02:31,129
Two years ago Chinese authorities officially
stated their intention

57
00:02:31,129 --> 00:02:33,540
to completely disregard that Declaration.

58
00:02:33,540 --> 00:02:37,349
But what is a surprise is just how many people

59
00:02:37,349 --> 00:02:39,999
came out to protest the extradition bill.

60
00:02:39,999 --> 00:02:42,689
A million people is a lot,

61
00:02:42,689 --> 00:02:45,749
especially in a city of only 7 million people.

62
00:02:45,749 --> 00:02:48,299
It was by far the biggest protest in Hong
Kong

63
00:02:48,299 --> 00:02:51,889
since it was handed over to China in 1997.

64
00:02:51,889 --> 00:02:52,889
So obviously,

65
00:02:52,889 --> 00:02:55,489
the most important question Chinese authorities
are asking is:

66
00:02:55,489 --> 00:02:59,120
Who’s behind this massive disruption to
social harmony?!

67
00:02:59,120 --> 00:03:02,120
Fortunately, state-run media has the answer!

68
00:03:02,120 --> 00:03:03,379
According to China Daily,

69
00:03:03,379 --> 00:03:05,180
it’s hostile foreign forces!

70
00:03:05,180 --> 00:03:07,680
They’re “seizing the opportunity to advance

71
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:10,650
their own strategy to hurt China

72
00:03:10,650 --> 00:03:13,689
by trying to create havoc in Hong Kong.”

73
00:03:13,689 --> 00:03:15,919
Now state-run media doesn’t specifically
name

74
00:03:15,919 --> 00:03:17,879
who those “foreign forces” are.

75
00:03:17,879 --> 00:03:19,989
But I’m going to assume they’re referring
to me.

76
00:03:19,989 --> 00:03:22,200
Well, me and the CIA.

77
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:23,200
That’s right,

78
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:26,370
United Front groups and pro-Chinese Communist
Party media

79
00:03:26,370 --> 00:03:29,339
have accused random foreigners in Hong Kong

80
00:03:29,339 --> 00:03:31,569
of being part of the CIA.

81
00:03:31,569 --> 00:03:32,569
Take it from me,

82
00:03:32,569 --> 00:03:34,909
those guys are not in the CIA.

83
00:03:34,909 --> 00:03:36,840
And what’s even better is that I’ve heard
from

84
00:03:36,840 --> 00:03:39,389
