Although I can’t take *all* of the credit.

90
00:03:51,010 --> 00:03:52,169
Because it was more than just a few

91
00:03:52,169 --> 00:03:53,980
China Uncensored fans in Hong Kong

92
00:03:53,980 --> 00:03:56,059
who joined Sunday’s ginormous march.

93
00:03:56,059 --> 00:03:58,750
And it was more than just students and activists,

94
00:03:58,750 --> 00:04:02,269
who were the bulk of the 2014 Umbrella Protests.

95
00:04:02,269 --> 00:04:05,919
This protest also included many ordinary Hongkongers.

96
00:04:05,919 --> 00:04:06,969
According to this poll,

97
00:04:06,969 --> 00:04:10,419
a third of the marchers had never protested
before.

98
00:04:10,419 --> 00:04:14,079
The extradition bill has even riled up many
of Hong Kong’s elite:

99
00:04:14,079 --> 00:04:15,980
businesspeople who feel that Hong Kong’s
rule of law

100
00:04:15,980 --> 00:04:20,100
is critical to the future of their corporate
interests.

101
00:04:20,100 --> 00:04:21,900
Even lawyers participated—

102
00:04:21,900 --> 00:04:25,210
following a smaller lawyers’ protest last
week.

103
00:04:25,210 --> 00:04:28,330
So basically, a huge cross section of Hong
Kong—

104
00:04:28,330 --> 00:04:30,580
including a lot of influential people—

105
00:04:30,580 --> 00:04:33,670
feel the extradition bill could affect them.

106
00:04:33,670 --> 00:04:35,470
And that’s what makes this different

107
00:04:35,470 --> 00:04:38,100
from many of the other protests Hong Kong
has seen

108
00:04:38,100 --> 00:04:39,970
over the last 20 years.

109
00:04:39,970 --> 00:04:42,670
It means everyone’s angry now.

110
00:04:42,670 --> 00:04:45,750
And it’s a big challenge to Hong Kong’s
leadership—

111
00:04:45,750 --> 00:04:47,600
especially Chief Executive Carrie Lam,

112
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:50,360
who’s the equivalent of Hong Kong’s governor.

113
